sentences: Agnieszka Duczmal (Polish pronunciation: [aɡˈɲɛʂka ˈdut͡ʂmal]; born 7 January 1946 in Krotoszyn, Poland) is a Polish conductor and founder of the Poznań Amadeus Orchestra.
She was born in 1946 in Krotoszyn where she spent the first nine years of her life.
She started to study conducting at the Academy of Music in Poznań in 1966 under Witold Krzemieński and graduated in 1971.

Still as a student, she founded a chamber orchestra in 1968.
Between 1971 and 1972 she was hired as assistant to the conductor at the Poznań Philharmonic.
The chamber orchestra conducted by her was taken over by the Polish Radio in 1977, renamed the "Amadeus Chamber Orchestra" in 1988.

Since 1972, she worked at the Poznań Grand Theatre where she was involved in staging the Polish premiere of Benjamin Britten's opera A Midsummer Night's Dream and Sergei Prokofiev's Romeo and Juliet.
She has been a jury member of many national and international music competitions including the Eurovision Young Musicians 2012 and the International Joseph Joachim Violin Competition.
In 1998, she was awarded the Commander's Cross of the Order of Polonia Restituta.
In 2002, she became the recipient of Brazil's highest order of merit –  the Order of the Southern Cross.
In 2005, she was awarded the Silver Medal for Merit to Culture – Gloria Artis.
In 2015, she was granted the title of an Honorary Citizen of the City of Poznań.
In 2018, she was received the Golden Fryderyk Award.
